1) What is a Factory Method in Java, and how does it use return types to create objects?
-->👉 Factory Method means: object creation is done inside a method, and we just call that method to get the object.
    👉 Factory method creates objects inside a method and returns them, instead of creating them directly in main.


    👉 A Factory Method is a method used to create and return objects instead of using new directly.

    ✅ How it uses return types:
    The method usually returns a parent type (interface/class)
    But internally creates different subclass objects
    ✅ Example
    interface Animal {
        void sound();
    }
    
    class Dog implements Animal {
        public void sound() {
            System.out.println("Bark");
        }
    }
    
    class Cat implements Animal {
        public void sound() {
            System.out.println("Meow");
        }
    }
    
    class AnimalFactory {
        static Animal getAnimal(String type) {
            if (type.equals("dog"))
                return new Dog();
            else
                return new Cat();
        }
    }
    
    👉 Return type = Animal
    👉 Returns = Dog or Cat (subclasses)



2) What types of values can a method return in Java, and how are they used in factory methods?
-->👉 A method in Java can return:

✅ Primitive types (int, double, etc.)
✅ Objects
✅ Arrays
✅ null
✅ Interface or abstract class types
🔥 In Factory Methods:

👉 Mostly return:

Interface or parent class type

✔️ This allows flexibility and polymorphism



